{"author":{"id":"60ed05ab465b316da1399b541adb6e896d0ccb4fee37f6abf3ea01d0c66b2c07"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1499298448,"nonce":"laaZgBv1ycNKi3SKYey5wWJGit4=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUyNDA4MDYyMTU=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1406","origin":"github"},"title":"HISAT2 wrapper default min score doesn't match HISAT2 default","message":"I was getting lower alignment rates than expected for some not-so-great data, so after some investigation I found that the min score in the wrapper is set to `C,0,0` (constant function, i.e. score must be at least 0), whereas the command-line default is `C,-18,0` (score must be at least -18). It made a huge difference for this data. I'm not an expert HISAT2 user by any means, but this difference in defaults seems fishy. \n\n\u003e -score-min \u003cfunc\u003e\nSets a function governing the minimum alignment score needed for an alignment to be considered \"valid\" (i.e. good enough to report). This is a function of read length. For instance, specifying L,0,-0.6 sets the minimum-score function f to f(x) = 0 + -0.6 * x, where x is the read length. See also: [setting function options]. The default is C,-18,0.","files":null}]}